source_code: After finding our archival description online, Evers' youngest son, Karsten Evers, contacted the Rubenianum in 2019. He had found this folder in a box with material of H. G. Evers that came to Karsten Evers after it was nearly thrown away at the Bildarchiv Marburg. He subsequently donated the folder to the Rubenianum.
Annotation: After finding our archival description online, Evers' youngest son, Karsten Evers, contacted the Rubenianum in 2019. He had found this folder in a box with material of H. G. Evers that came to Karsten Evers after it was nearly thrown away at the Bildarchiv Marburg. He subsequently donated the folder to the Rubenianum.

Start Date Note: Evers' son Karsten Evers dated the (front sides of the) documents before the publication of his book on Rubens in 1942, referring to the fact that he didn't work deeply in research on Rubens anymore after WWII.

Description:
The folder contains handwritten, very detailed, timelines on Rubens' life and work, with references to his network, travelling, commissions and seemingly also references to his correspondence. They are the manuscript for the first chapter, 'Zeittafeln', in Evers' publication [*Rubens und sein Werk : neue Forschungen*](https://anet.be/record/rub/opacrub/c:lvd:13258322/N).   
There seem to be tree versions: one (with a red screen) starting in 1612 and ending in 1640 (the early years and 1613 are missing); the second one (with the pages numbered unevenly) starting in 1602 and ending in 1641; and the last one (rather small and multiple years per page) starting in 1600 and ending in 1641 (with a gap between 1608 and 1629, so probably a part is missing). 

The back sides of the pages were used to create a 19th-century timeline later on in Evers' career.

Title: Folder "Zeittafeln 19. Jht. - dafür benutzt die Rückseiten von: Zeittaflen für Rubens" (inscription on cover by Evers)
